{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Microtubules are polymers of tubulin, a dimer of two 55kDa subunits, designated alpha and beta [[cite:PUB00000039], [cite:PUB00000978]]. Within the microtubule lattice, α-β heterodimers associate in a head-to-tail fashion, giving rise to microtubule polarity. Fluorescent labelling studies have suggested that tubulin is oriented in microtubules with beta-tubulin toward the plus end [[cite:PUB00006112]]. For maximal rate and extent of polymerisation into microtubules, tubulin requires GTP. Two molecules of GTP are bound at different sites, termed N and E. At the E (Exchangeable) site, GTP is hydrolysed during incorporation into the microtubule. Close to the E site is an invariant region rich in glycine residues, which is found in both chains and is thought to control access of the nucleotide to its binding site [[cite:PUB00002443]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036525", "name" "Tubulin/FtsZ, GTPase domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"} {"accession" "IPR037103", "name" "Tubulin/FtsZ-like, C-terminal domain", "type" "homologous_superfamily"} {"accession" "IPR008280", "name" "Tubulin/FtsZ, C-terminal", "type" "homologous_superfamily"} {"accession" "IPR023123", "name" "Tubulin, C-terminal", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"prints" {"PR01162" "ALPHATUBULIN"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Alpha tubulin", "short" "Alpha_tubulin"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 647, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 2721, "taxa" 12600, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 277763, "sets" 0, "proteins" 26595, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 17855}, "pathways" 194}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"ec" {"displayName" "ENZYME", "description" "ENZYME is a repository of information relative to the nomenclature of enzymes. It is pri